 that bridges the conventional period boundaries, the collection participates in an exchange between medievalists and early modernists that seeks to generate a dialogic encounter between the periods with the aim of further dismantling the rigid notions of chronology and periodisation that have kept medieval and early modern scholarship apart.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aMedieval Studies 2020. 4aShakespeare 2018. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh  aChaucer.  aNew Historicist paradigm.  aShakespeare.  aTroilus and Criseyde.  aanticipatory emotion.  aauthorial humility.  aearly modern fiction.  aemotion.  agendered female.  ahermeneutical acts.  alate medieval Troy tradition.  aliterary combat.  aliterary narratives.  aliterary studies.  amedieval fiction.  amilitary combat.  asententiousness.  asexual frustration.  atemporality.  atradition.1 aDrakakis, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Andrew James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Andrew James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKeller, Wolfram R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKempf, Elisabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLees-Jeffries, Hester, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLobsien, Verena Olejniczak, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMahler, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimpson, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrohm, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTrigg, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary